<hr>
<h2>Hilton Head Study: Citrin&#174; 75</h2>
<p>In 1994, we conducted an eight-week study on 75 volunteers
taking Citrin&#174;75 (a supplement consisting of 250 mg
(-)-hydroxycitrate and 100&Ecirc;mcg chromium from Chromium
Picolinate). The study group included 60 women and 15 men who
ranged in age from 21 to 65 years, and in weight from 135.5 to
253 pounds.<br>
All subjects were in reasonably good health when the project
began. However, 74 percent had abnormal blood chemistry (mainly
in the form of elevated lipid levels) and 53 percent were taking
one or more prescription drugs for medical conditions primarily
associated with elevated lipid levels and body overweight. Before
the study started, only two volunteers showed detectable chromium
in their blood. Despite the &quot;normal&quot; diet most
participants claimed to be following before our study began,
their plasma levels indicated a virtual absence of this important
trace mineral. As many people are now well aware of, chromium,
which is required by the body to regulate blood sugar, helps
prevent hyperglycemia that can lead to diabetes mellitus.<br>
The identical protocol (described for the previous studies)
consisting of sensible eating habits as specified in the Smart
Choice Diet, adequate dietary water intake, and laboratory work
and monitoring was used, along with a dietary supplement of
Citrin&#174; which was taken before each meal. Patient profiles
taken during this study involved compliance monitoring and blood
chemistry panels, including an analysis of plasma chromium
levels.</p>
<hr>
<h2>Summary of Results</h2>
<p>a) Forty-two (42) subjects who completed the study and for who
the laboratory data were available lost an average of 10.80
pounds per person.<br>
b) Only two (2) out of the 42 subjects had any detectable plasma
chromium levels. At the end of the eight week period, all 42
subjects had significant and measurable levels of chromium in
their plasma.<br>
c) Ten (10) subjects whose laboratory data are still being
evaluated lost an average of 10.60 pounds per person.<br>
d) Another six (6) subjects who stayed on the program for only
six weeks lost only 5.8 pounds per person for that period.<br>
e) The study had a total attrition of 17 subjects who dropped out
for various personal reasons.<br>
f) Of the 42 subjects who completed the study, 11 showed
statistically significant reductions in their cholesterol levels.
Cholesterol levels increased moderately in nine cases and
remained unaltered in 22 cases.<br>
g) Triglyceride levels dropped in 11 cases (statistically
significant) and were elevated moderately in six cases. In the
remaining cases, the changes observed were not significant.<br>
h) Glucose levels were reduced significantly in eight cases,
slightly elevated in two cases, and virtually unchanged in 30
cases.<br>
i) It is reasonable to conclude that Citrin&#174; plus Chromium
Picolinate in the doses used in this study and in combination
with an appropriate diet and exercise plan can facilitate weight
loss.</p>
<hr>
<h2>SAFETY OF CITRIN&#174;</h2>
<p><em>Muhammed Majeed, Ph.D.</em></p>
<p>Citrin&#174; has been tested and approved by manufacturers in
the United States and Europe as a safe and efficacious product.
It is the only herbal supplement derived from Garcinia cambogia
to have undergone human clinical trials in the U.S.A. Its potency
is guaranteed through state-of-the-art HPLC.<br>
The LD50 Value of (-)HCA is &gt; 2000 mg/kg for intraperitonial
administration and &gt; 4000 mg/kg for oral administration.
Tolerance to anorexic, or appetite suppressant drugs, usually
develops over time. This is a common feature in Central Nervous
System (CNS)-stimulant drugs such as amphetamines and other
phenylethylamine derivatives. In contrast, tolerance to
Citrin&#174; in pre-clinical studies was minimal. In one
investigation, (-)-hydroxycitrate continued to lower the amount
of food consumed through the 80-day duration of the trial. Other
anorexic agents such as Fenfluramine were effective for appetite
only after the first few days, but not beyond that period of
time.<br>
(-)-Hydroxycitrate does not affect respiration, phosphorylation,
or the citrate synthesis of the reconstituted mitochondria. This
compound lowers the rate of lipogenesis (or the rate at which the
body forms new fat) in a dose-dependent manner in the liver,
adipose (fat) tissue, and the small intestine. However,
(-)-hydroxycitrate neither penetrates the mitochondria nor
affects normal energy production.<br>
As an herbal product containing standardized (-)HCA, Citrin&#174;
offers a safe alternative to appetite-suppressant substances that
overactivate the sympathetic nervous system, produce only short
term anorexia, and carry the risk of being addictive. Unlike
pharmaceutical agents and most other nutrient and herbal products
on the market, Citrin&#174; decreases food intake, diminishes
appetite, and accelerates the burning of fatty acids without
adverse side effects. These features make Citrin&#174; a viable
choice for efficaciously treating obesity and overweightness.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>WEIGHT CONTROL: A BARIATRICIAN&#146;S POINT OF VIEW</strong></h3>
<p><em>Anthony Conte, M.D.</em></p>
<h3>Why Do Some People Get Fat While Others Don&#146;t?</h3>
<p>There is an increasing number of theories &Ntilde; most of
them speculative &Ntilde; about weight gain and the manner in
which calories are ingested and burned. We are all aware of the
many non-obese people who overeat, especially consuming huge
quantities of carbohydrates, for extended periods of time without
gaining any weight. However, even in individuals who maintain
stable weight, this pattern ultimately is costly to normal
health. Given a long enough period of time, excessive intake of
carbohydrates will lead to excess storage of body fat. This
occurs because over consumption of glucose-containing foods
increases the body&#146;s production of lipogenic, or
fat-storing, enzymes such as lipoprotein lipase (LPL). Once this
chemical action can be safely blocked without disrupting any of
the body&#146;s other normal processes, then most weight problems
can be brought under control.<br>
Simple refined sugars, including fructose which is often touted
as a natural sugar since it is found in fruit, are always a
problem for weight management. Indeed, there is growing evidence
that fructose stimulates lipogenesis, or fat storage, even more
than does glucose. White sugar is composed of two glucose
molecules joined together. Fructose is converted even more
rapidly into glucose than is white, or refined sugar. Fructose,
present in fruit juices, corn syrups, and many so-called
&quot;health food products,&quot; causes an unhealthy rise in the
levels of liver enzymes, insulin, and blood triglycerides.<br>
Physical activity is of course critical to proper weight
management. Metabolic rate, the ratio of lean to fatty body mass,
and genetic factors (or individual heredity) in combination with
physical activity have bearing on how successful -- or
unsuccessful body fat reduction will be. Equally important to
weight management are the degree, duration, and timing of
overeating. When physical exercise is closely coupled with the
timing of excessive eating, then the negative consequences of
potential weight gain are minimized. People who diet without
exercising tend to lose mainly water and in some cases, muscle
tissue; but, individuals who exercise and eat a sensible and
balanced diet low in simple sugars are able to effectively shed
excess weight, and, most importantly, keep it off for sustained
periods of time.<br>
I have used various Citrin&#174;-based products to treat numerous
cases of overweightness in my medical practice. I have found
unequivocally from the case studies I have followed and the
clinical studies I have conducted that Citrin&#174; is a safe and
effective natural alternative to allopathic drugs for promoting
weight loss.</p>
